{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Algeria-Canada|Algeria|Canada|filetype=svg}}
'''Algeria–Canada relations''' refer to [[Interstate relations]] between [[Algeria]] and [[Canada]]. Canada recognized Algeria following its independence from France in 1962, and formal diplomatic relations were established two years later in 1964.

== Bilateral Visits ==
[[File:Algeria, Ottawa.JPG|thumb|right|Embassy of Algeria in Ottawa]]
In 2006, Governor General [[Michaëlle Jean]] visited Algeria as part of a tour of Africa, during which she promoted the partnership between Canada and Algeria in assisting in African development.<ref>[http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/acdi-cida.nsf/eng/RAC-111616820-SSR Governor General Michaëlle Jean represents Canada on state visit to sub-Saharan and North Africa - Canadian International Development Agency (CIDA)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2010, Algerian President [[Abdelaziz Bouteflika]] visited Canada to take part in the [[36th G8 summit|G8 summit]] in [[Muskoka]].<ref>[http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/summit/2010muskoka/delegations.html Muskoka Participants<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Lawrence Cannon]], then the Minister of Foreign Affairs, visited Algeria in January 2011 and met with his Algerian counterpart, Minister of Foreign Affairs Mourad Medelci.

== Economic Activity ==

Algeria is Canada's top trading partner in Africa. There is a large [[trade imbalance]] between Algeria and Canada in favour of the Algerians. Canadian exports to Algeria totalled $352 million in 2010, mostly in agricultural products such as [[Durum wheat]], while Canadian imports from Algeria totalled $3.8 billion, 99% of which was crude oil. 
<ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/Content/LOP/ResearchPublications/2010-45-e.htm#a1 Canadian Trade and Investment Activity: Canada–Algeria (2010-45E)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

== Migration ==

The Algerian community in Canada numbers approximately 50,000 people, most of whom reside in and around [[Montreal]]. [[Air Algérie]] operates one daily flight from Montreal to Algiers to serve this market.

== Security ==
{{main|In Amenas hostage crisis}}
Algeria claimed that two Canadians were among the Jihadi militants responsible for a hostage taking at an isolated natural gas plant in the [[Sahara desert]] in January 2013.  Canada launched its own investigation. In March, the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|RCMP]] confirmed that one Canadian's body was identified to be related to the attack.  The investigation was slowed by the fact that Canada and Algeria do not share intelligence information.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2013/03/18/canadian-killed-in-algeria.html Canadian died during Algerian gas plant attack, RCMP say]</ref>

== Resident diplomatic missions ==

* Algeria has an embassy in [[Ottawa]] and a consulate-general in [[Montreal]].<ref>[http://www.ambalgott.com Embassy of Algeria in Ottawa]</ref>
* Canada has an embassy in [[Algiers]].<ref>[http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/algeria-algerie/index.aspx?lang=eng Embassy of Canada in Algiers]</ref>

== See also ==
* [[Algerian Canadians]]

