{{Politics of Luxembourg}}
The 12 '''[[canton (subnational entity)|cantons]]''' ({{lang-fr|cantons}}, {{lang-de|Kantone}}, {{lang-lb|Kantounen}}) of the [[Luxembourg|Grand Duchy of Luxembourg]] are areas of local government at the first level of [[Local administrative unit]] (LAU-1) in the [[European Union]]'s [[Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics]] for [[Eurostat]] purposes. They were subdivisions of the three [[Districts of Luxembourg]] until 2015, when the district level of government was abolished. The cantons are in turn subdivided into 102 [[Communes of Luxembourg|communes]] (i.e. municipalities).
==List== {{stack|[[Image:Groothertogdom LuxemburgKantons.png|right]]}}
The following list gives the names of the cantons in French and Luxembourgish (in that order) which are both official languages of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg:
In the former [[Diekirch District]]: *[[Clervaux (canton)|Clervaux]]/Klierf (2) *[[Diekirch (canton)|Diekirch]]/Dikrech (3) *[[Redange (canton)|Redange]]/Réiden (9) *[[Vianden (canton)|Vianden]]/Veianen (11) *[[Wiltz (canton)|Wiltz]]/Wolz (12)
In the former [[Grevenmacher District]]: *[[Echternach (canton)|Echternach]]/Iechternach (4) *[[Grevenmacher (canton)|Grevenmacher]]/Gréiwemaacher (6) *[[Remich (canton)|Remich]]/Réimech (10)
In the former [[Luxembourg District]]: *[[Capellen (canton)|Capellen]]/Capellen (1) *[[Esch-sur-Alzette (canton)|Esch-sur-Alzette]]/Esch-Uelzecht (5) *[[Luxembourg (canton)|Luxembourg]]/Lëtzebuerg (7) *[[Mersch (canton)|Mersch]]/Miersch (8)
