{{more citations needed|date=December 2016}} {{Infobox prepared food | name = Halušky | image = Bryndzové halušky so slaninou.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = Bryndzové Halušky with bacon | alternate_name = | country = | region = | creator = | course = | type = [[Dumpling]] or [[noodle]], [[gnocchi]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Batter (cooking)|batter]] ([[flour]], water) | variations = [[Bryndzové halušky]], [[strapačky]] | calories = | other = }} [[File:Halusky strainer without text.jpg|right|thumb|Halušky strainer]] [[File:Poltawa Galushka Monument.jpg|right|thumb|Halušky monument in [[Poltava]], Ukraine]]
'''Halušky''' ({{IPA-cs|ɦaluʃkɪ|IPA}} in [[Czech language|Czech]] and [[Slovak language|Slovak]], singular: ''haluška''; {{lang-hu|galuska}}, ''haluska'' or ''nokedli''; {{lang-ro|gălușcă}}; {{lang-sr|galuška}}; {{lang-uk|галушка}}; {{lang-lt|virtinukai}}) are a traditional variety of thick, soft [[noodle]]s or [[dumpling]]s cooked in the Central and Eastern European cuisines ([[Slovakia]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://travel.spectator.sk/articles/327/ |title=Halušky: Humble King of the Slovak Kitchen |first=Rachel |last=Salaman |accessdate=2008-09-11 |work=Spectacular Slovakia |year=2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spectator.sk/articles/view/11624/9/ |title=Halušky: Like gnocchi only smaller and tastier |first=Rachel |last=Salaman |accessdate=2008-09-11 |work=[[The Slovak Spectator]] |date=2003-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spectator.sk/articles/view/4209/9/ |title=Three liters of bryndzové halušky small work for hefty men in national eating competition |first=Matt |last=Reynolds |accessdate=2008-09-11 |work=[[The Slovak Spectator]] |date=1999-06-21}}</ref> [[Czech Republic]], [[Poland]], [[Serbia]], [[Ukraine]], [[Lithuania]], [[Romania]] and [[Hungary]]). Halušky can refer to the dumplings themselves, or to the complete dish.
==Preparation== The dumplings can be made from dough spread in a thin layer on a wooden cutting board, then cut and scraped off in small pieces which are dropped into boiling water. They can also be made with a special perforated halušky strainer forming small (1/2 &times; 2–3&nbsp;cm) irregularly-shaped lumps which drop directly into boiling water as a thinner batter-like dough is pressed through the openings of the strainer.
Although recipes vary from region to region, in general [[flour]] is mixed with water to form a [[Batter (cooking)|batter]]. Finely grated [[potato]]es can be added to the batter. Eggs may be added, but Slovak [[bryndzové halušky]] do not contain them. Flour and mashed potatoes are enough to form a batter. After cooking, they are mixed with various ingredients, such as cheese, meat, [[butter]], cabbage, onions, or combinations of these.
==Variations== [[Bryndzové halušky]] is a traditional [[Slovak cuisine|Slovak]] dish also found in [[Moravia]] in the eastern part of the [[Czech cuisine|Czech Republic]]. [[Strapačky]] is a similar Slovak dish, where stewed sauerkraut is used instead of bryndza. In Hungary, galuska are often eaten with meat stews, such as [[goulash]] or [[pörkölt]].
In the [[United States]], most adapted halusky recipes call for egg noodles rather than potato dumplings. Some American cooks include loose, cut, and fried green cabbage (a convergence with [[strapačky]], compelled by simplicity, difficulty in finding [[bryndza]] or acceptable substitutes, and access to affordable cabbage in areas with prominent existing Slavic and Germanic immigration).
==See also== *[[Gnocchi]] *[[Kluski]], a [[Polish cuisine|Polish]] dumpling *[[Passatelli]] *[[Spätzle]] *[[Strapačky]]
