'''''Journey to Ararat''''' ({{lang-et|Teekond Araratile}}) is a 2011 [[Estonia]]n [[documentary film]] directed, written, and produced by [[Riho Västrik]].<ref name="efis">{{et icon}} {{cite web|title=''Teekond Araratile'' (2011)|url=http://www.efis.ee/et/filmiliigid/film/id/11617/huvitavat-lugemist|work=Estonian Film Database|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ter-Sahakian|first=Karine|url=http://www.panarmenian.net/eng/details/177415/|title=Armenian community of Estonia: A look into the future|work=[[PanARMENIAN.Net]]|date=29 March 2014|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>  In the film, Västrik travels to [[Armenia]] and [[Turkey]] with Estonian scholar Erki Tammiksaar to retrace the footsteps of [[Baltic Germans|Baltic German]] explorer [[Friedrich Parrot]] and [[Armenians|Armenian]] writer [[Khachatur Abovian]] on their historic ascent of [[Mount Ararat]] in 1829.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.looduskalender.ee/en/node/11879|title=Nights are long and dark|work=Looduskalender.ee|date=29 March 2014|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>  The film derives its name from Parrot's account of his expedition, ''Journey to Ararat'' ({{lang-de|Reise zum Ararat}}).<ref name="efis"/> It was screened at the [[Yerevan International Film Festival|Golden Apricot International Film Festival]] in [[Yerevan]] in 2013.<ref name="apricot">{{cite web|title='Journey to Ararat' Documentary Film|url=http://www.gaiff.am/en/1372752465|accessdate=24 April 2017|newspaper=[[Yerevan International Film Festival|Golden Apricot International Film Festival]]|date=July 2013}}</ref>

